##Italy's health CARE SYSTEM UNDER EPIDEMIC: admission, medicine and wards

Micro signal

Function introduction, reach consensus, create theory, make route, put forward program, establish principle

Italy enjoys universal free health care, is among the best in the world, and has an average life expectancy of 82.7 years. However, since the outbreak of NCP, the rapid rise in the number of confirmed cases, the high mortality rate and the shortage of health care resources in the hard hit areas in the north are both worrying and worrying: What is the actual state of Health Care Resources in Italy? Will the health care system be able to withstand the impact of the epidemic? In the absence of foreign aid, what mobile resources can be deployed? Has the Ministry of Health taken remedial measures in a timely manner?

This article will start from the basic resources of the Italian health system before the outbreak, by integrating information on the epidemic response process, the current situation of resource consumption and the preparation of additional resources, etc. , the impact of the new crown disease and the health system's efforts to combat it were described.

- Introduction to health system -

Overview

The current Italian health care system was established in 1978, matured in the 1980s and 1990s, and has been undergoing changes in recent years. Article 32 of the Constitution, which grants the right to health to all Italian citizens, is the legal basis for the health care system and system. Italy ranks ninth out of 195 countries in the Lancet's 2018 ranking of the quality of care in the world, it has performed well in terms of national financial investment, the average number of medical personnel per 1,000 inhabitants, the allocation of medical resources, the efficiency of disease treatment, the incidence of chronic diseases, the survival rate of cancer and the life expectancy of residents.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Figure Note 1

Italy's health care system is divided into central and local (that is, regions) two main levels. The Central Competent Authority is the Ministry of Health, which is in charge of the health service throughout the country, but with full respect for the constitutional autonomy of the localities. In addition to the Ministry of Health, the central health system comprises more than a dozen other institutions, including the Higher Institute of Health (ISS) in Rome, which is responsible for reviewing confirmed cases during the outbreak of NCP. Local health authorities (ASL) have some autonomy under the unified directive to provide health care to the public through local health authorities and hospitals, services include infectious disease prevention, vaccination, outpatient and specialist care, social care, mental health services, palliative care, and more. Italy's health-care resources also show huge imbalances based on regional distribution. The overall level of health in the more developed areas in the north is significantly higher than in the Lazio region in the south and centre.

On an individual basis, residents can register with the local health authorities to participate in the Italian health system and enjoy national health insurance, have a health insurance card and choose a family doctor (MEDICO DI base) or paediatrician. The family doctor is usually a general practitioner in a contractual partnership with the local health board. Some family doctors are not affiliated with any medical institution and work in independently operated outpatient clinics (Ambulatorio) , there are also family doctors who work with doctors in different specialties at the Poliambulatori. As a part of the basic medical services, family doctors are mainly responsible for the initial diagnosis and prescription of common minor diseases, special referral booking for other diseases, home visits and so on. Patients with a specialist referral need to make an appointment with a specialist at a higher level hospital through the Centro Unico di Prenotazione, or CUP, cup offers a wide range of booking options online, over the phone, and in person (a collaborative family doctor and pharmacy or hospital counter) .

In more urgent cases, patients can skip the family doctor and contact the emergency doctor on call for services. In more urgent cases, patients can go by themselves or by ambulance to the PRONTO SOCCORSO via the 118 emergency line, and then enter the waiting or seeing procedure according to the initial check-up by the triage nurse. Emergency services may be operated and directed by different higher authorities (regional emergency medical boards, local health boards or 118 operating centres) in different regions, however, the ambulance and first aid personnel usually come from social partners, private enterprises or voluntary associations (such as the Red Cross) , and doctors / nurses from the public sector can travel with them, depending on the circumstances, the public sector also provides helicopter rescue services for 118 first aid in special emergencies.

Capital

In particular, the citizens'health care system adopts a multi-track structure. The first is the United States Public Health Service, which is open to all citizens and aims to be broad, equal and fair. The second is the Insurance Medical Fund, which is invested by companies or individuals and is used only to supplement medical funds and is not used for profit Finally, there is the extra cost of health insurance for individual citizens.

There are two main sources of funding for public health care: Taxes and revenue from health care services. The former accounts for about 14 per cent of public expenditure, while the latter includes payments made by patients for diagnosis and treatment in health-care institutions, with the state granting exemptions or reimbursements depending on, inter alia, the economic situation of the patients. About half of this medical funding is allocated locally, the other half goes mainly to hospitals, and about 5 per cent goes to community-based disease prevention. According to 2018 statistics, about 23.7 per cent of health care costs come from private citizens'spending, the proportion and amount of government spending is among the highest in the world, but lower than the average of other EU countries. The cost of testing in Italy is 30 euros 5 for the new outbreak of pneumonia, which is fully covered by the Italian state; a bed in an intensive care unit costs between 1,200 and 1,500 euros 6 a day, the cost of intensive care in Italy is about $20,000 per person, based on about two weeks of intensive care per patient.

Italy's high rate of severe illness (8.5%) and mortality (6.8%) put a strain on the health system. As of 18:00 on 15 March, the total number of patients in Italy was 11,335, of whom 1,672 were in intensive care, with nearly half concentrated in Lombardy ËßÅ LombardiaÔºåReg. . 7. The state has allocated 25 billion euros to the emergency response, but beyond the financial problems, the number of hospital beds in the hard hit areas in the north is in dire need.

Bed Space

According to the public health system's 2017 annual report, there are 169978 beds in Italy, with an average of only 3.7 beds per 1,000 people, compared with 12.27 in South Korea, nearly four times as many as in Italy, germany also tops the list with 8.3 cards per 1,000 people (World Bank figure) . 10.

In addition to public hospitals, private hospitals and medical institutions also account for a large proportion. Private health care provides 26.5 per cent of Italian health care and accounts for 17 per cent of the total health system allocation. The private sector has 39,079 beds, or 22% of the total, and 1,300 intensive care beds.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Figure Note 4

But the already tight number of beds and the number of health care workers is falling year after year. This is related to the reduction of medical funding, the lack of investment in medical professional education, the flight of young doctors, and the aging of the age structure of the health care workforce.

Italy will need 4,000 intensive care beds in three to four weeks, according to projections published in the Lancet by the Mario Negri Research Institute in collaboration with the University of Bergamo. How has Italy's health system responded to the crisis of the new crown disease, already weak and overwhelmed?

- Diagnosis and treatment in new Crown Disease -

Overall process

Italy has also followed the aforementioned hierarchy in the admission process, with the central and local authorities playing their respective roles. Patients with suspected symptoms of new crown pneumonia can call the new Crown Disease Advisory Line 1500 set up by the Ministry of Health for treatment assistance 12, the gendarmerie line 112, the emergency line 118 also receive emergency reports of the epidemic. In addition, the local health authorities (ASL) in various districts will take the initiative to track down and test close contacts of confirmed cases. Suspected patients may also report their condition and seek assistance through the local green hotline or ASL registered family doctors.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
1. Testing

Detection shunt

The operator or family doctor collects information from the new coronavirus infection risk assessment and self-assessment form to determine the severity of the disease and match the patient to the appropriate treatment, or to the appropriate hospital department. If the symptoms of mild illness, patients can stay at home, under the guidance of a general practitioner at home treatment (see below for details) .

For patients who need to go to hospital, Italian hospitals have set up Tenda pre-triage tents in front of emergency rooms to avoid the risk of cross-infection. Its role is to assess the physical condition of patients before they enter the hospital. Inside the tent are a doctor, a nurse and a social health worker. All patients will first be placed in a pre-triage tent, followed by temperature and medical history checks. Patients who do not show signs of new pneumonia will be transferred to the emergency room for routine treatment, if the patient does show signs of new pneumonia, the medical staff will skip the emergency department and communicate directly with the doctor in charge of the Infectious Diseases Department to determine the patient's whereabouts, they are usually housed in general or sub-critical beds for infectious diseases; in severe cases, they are sent directly to the intensive-care unit.

Detection Standard

Italian authorities by reference to the Korean Center for Disease Control and Prevention (KCDC) detection model, "targeted, rapid, early detection" as a principle 13. Sampling should be carried out strictly by professionals, most of which should be done in the home of the reporter, or by professionals to take the reporter to the designated hospital for sampling. As described in the 40th press release (see Article)15, according to the Ministry of Health Decision 16, Italy does not currently test asymptomatic people. This is in line with the European Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (ECDC) test standard 17, which requires both "symptomatic" and "exposure history" to be met; in particularly severe cases, people who do not have exposure history also need to be tested. However, the ECDC also points out that previously asymptomatic positive people should also be included in the statistics, as reflected in the report of the Institute of Health (ISS) .

Detection Capability

The first post-sampling test is carried out by a regional Reference Laboratory or a certified virus laboratory with the same testing qualification in the area 19. In addition to the 15 regional reference laboratories, the virus laboratories responsible for the first preliminary screening tests 20, the authorities are now also mobilizing the microbiological and viral laboratories with the same detection level throughout the country, accredited by the Institute of Higher Health (ISS) in Rome, to participate in the diagnostic work of the epidemic prevention, including laboratories in medical institutions and universities, a total of 4421. Because current testing techniques can give a false-positive error of about 1-4 per cent, samples that are positive at the initial test are sent to the ISS for re-examination and the final result is communicated to the authorities.

The throat swab sampling kit currently in use in Italy was developed and produced by Brescia's Copan 22. Throat Swabs are inactivated in the virus lab, RNA is extracted, PCR (polymerase chain reaction) amplification and analysis are performed, and the computer outputs the results in about four hours and 23 hours. The authorities are also waiting for BATM, an Israeli biotechnology company, to have its new coronary pneumonia diagnostic kit certified as a European CE medical device, which will be produced later in Rome by Adaltis, the Republic reported, the new kit can reduce the cost of testing to 0.26 euros.

2. Home Quarantine

On March 7,2020, the rome-based Institute of Advanced Health announced measures 25 for home quarantine for at least 14 days in order to avoid the spread of the epidemic and overload of the medical system. There are two categories of people who need to be isolated at home:

* People who have had close contact with NCP include those who are asymptomatic, have mild symptoms and test positive, have mild symptoms and test negative
* Who have recovered and been discharged from hospital but are still positive

People who have been in close contact with NCP include those who are asymptomatic, have mild symptoms and test positive, have mild symptoms and test negative

Who have recovered and been discharged from hospital but are still positive

Home Segregation of the parties required the assistance of public health workers, the implementation of the detailed rules see the last push, that is, "interpretation of the decree" (Click to see Article)26. In short, the home isolation of the parties should strictly adhere to the wearing of masks, avoid contact, disinfection and other health norms, morning and evening twice temperature, and public health workers or general practitioners to communicate the emergence of new symptoms. When direct contact with others in the same space is unavoidable, such as a nursing mother or an elderly person in need of assistance and persons with mobility disabilities, they should clean themselves and protect themselves.

Home Segregation is essentially a form of trust segregation, which is assisted by society, including assessment of living conditions and the adequacy of protective equipment, assistance to unsupervised persons and psychological assistance to isolated groups.

3. Hospitalization

Place of admission

In order to facilitate the admission of new-onset pneumonia patients, the regions prepare their own admission plans and arrange public and private medical institutions. Take the Emilia region of Romagn√©, for example, where there are five levels of bed saturation 27:

* First, use existing beds to isolate patients;
* Second Class, the same kind of patients are concentrated in hospital;
* (C) at level 3, the expansion of sectors and institutions with a specific large region, the transfer and suspension of non-urgent, deferrable medical activities among them and the creation of more space available for the needs of the epidemic;
* Level four, which uses an inter-district network to move patients from the most saturated hospitals to those with higher availability.
* Level 5, the establishment of a hospital or diagnostic and therapeutic building for new-onset pneumonia patients: these are small and medium-sized buildings (approximately 150-200 beds) with intensive or semi-intensive care beds.

First, the use of existing beds to isolate patients;

Second, the same kind of patients are concentrated in hospital;

At the third level, the expansion of sectors and institutions in large regions and the relocation and suspension of non-urgent, deferrable medical activities to make more space available for the needs of the epidemic;

At the fourth level, an inter-district network is used to transfer patients from the most saturated hospitals to those with higher availability.

Level 5, the establishment of a hospital or diagnostic and therapeutic building for patients with NCP: These are small and medium-sized buildings (about 150-200 beds) with intensive or semi-intensive care beds.

The utilization of hospital resources in the region varies with the epidemic situation. Outside the existing HUB across the region, some hospitals (or departments) have been transformed into Ospedale Covid. In the region of Romagn√©, for example, the distribution of new pneumonia specialist hospitals is: Piacenza (3) , Parma, Reggio (2) , Modena, Bologna (2) , Ferrara, Romagn√© (5) , about six hospitals are on standby at the same time.

In addition, the Italian Ministry of Defence, based in military hospitals throughout the country, 28 confirmed on 3 March that 2,200 wards and 6,600 beds were available for the treatment of patients with new-onset pneumonia and that military doctors and nurses would be assigned to the central epidemic area.

Additional Ward

With the assistance of the Civil Defense Department and the Ministry of National Defense, several regions are adding intensive care beds, sub-intensive care beds, ordinary beds and isolation monitoring facilities as soon as possible to deal with the increasingly severe epidemic. Private hospital associations across Italy have joined forces to fight the disease, at the initiative of Maurizio Landini, Secretary General of the General Confederation of Labour. Lombardy's private hospital has already cleared 70% of its non emergency beds for 29 new patients, including 223 critical care beds, and another 150 will be treated shortly.

Patient metastasis

According to the evening post 30, Lombardy ËßÅ LombardiaÔºåReg. has started to transfer new cases of coronary pneumonia in stable clinical conditions to out-of-hospital care settings, such as institutions specialising in lung rehabilitation or social health facilities such as nursing homes. The criteria were: no life threatening arrhythmias, hemoglobin above 7% , body temperature below 37 ¬∞C, Platelet and white blood cell counts in the normal range and no indication for surgery or high risk of pulmonary embolism.

In addition, in order to reduce the medical burden in Lombardy ËßÅ LombardiaÔºåReg. , there are also some serious patients who have been transferred to other regions for further intensive-care unit treatment. With the assistance of Civil Defense Commissioner, Angelo Borrelli, and Italy's CROSS, 31, ambulances and helicopters were used to transport 30 patients to the regions of Lazio, Liguria, Tuscany, Friuli, Piedmont and Apulia. When patients are moved, small intensive care units need to be placed inside the vehicle, as well as specialist medical staff, who are currently scarce.

Treatment, drugs and medical devices

Treatment depends on the severity of the patient's symptoms 32. For patients with the most severe complications (about 10% of the total) , intensive-care unit assistance with ventilation is required. For patients with insufficient oxygen saturation, non-invasive ventilation tools are used to support aspiration function. For patients who do not respond adequately to oxygen therapy, CPAP is used. For patients who do not respond adequately to CPAP, invasive mechanical ventilation can be further developed if there is severe hypoxia.

In the most severe cases, consider using an Extracorporeal Membrane Oxygenation (ECMO) device, which draws blood to an external machine and oxygenates it, and immediately reinfuses it while resting the heart and lungs. In addition to respiratory support, the intensive-care unit ensures that the patient continues to eat, take medication, and, if necessary, channel fluid from the brain, chest, and abdomen.

On March 3, the Public Administration Procurement Centre (CONSIP) closed a tender for the provision of 3,918 suction machines for critical and sub-critical care services in hospitals. The first 119 machines were delivered on March 12,200 in four to seven days, 886 in eight to fifteen days, and 2,713 in 16 to 45 days. SIARE Engineering provided 300 pieces of equipment.

On Drugs 33, Italy will participate in two phase III clinical trials promoted by Gilead Sciences to assess the efficacy and safety of the Radzivir test molecule in hospitalized adults with a confirmed diagnosis of new coronary pneumonia. The study will initially be carried out at the SACO hospital in Milan, the San Mateo General Hospital in Pavia, the hospital company of Padua, the University Hospital of Parma and the National Institute of Medical Science of Lazzaro Lanzani in Rome. Italy, in cooperation with the Italian Drug Administration (AIFA) , is in the process of separating out other medical centres in areas of severe neocoronavirus infection for inclusion in the study. As regulators have not yet approved the use of Ridgeville outside clinical trials, non-pilot hospitals are currently only allowed to administer the drug to patients with NCP in severe emergencies when there is no other effective treatment option.

4. Patients with other diseases (chronic diseases, maternity, emergency)

Despite the strain, Italy has not stopped treating patients with other diseases. The Lombardy region has designated 18 hub hospitals 34 for other non-ncp emergency patients, including major trauma, neurosurgery, neurostroke, interventional cardiology, cardiac surgery and vascular surgery emergencies. Hub Hospitals must ensure round-the-clock care for critically ill patients who can not be delayed and the operation of multiple reliable teams, at least one of the teams will need to ensure isolation and independent access to treatment for patients with possible new pneumonia. Other public and private institutions may collaborate upon approval and conclusion of contracts. At the same time, the hub has reduced non-emergency clinics and surgeries to ensure a concentration of TCM in the treatment of critically ill patients, such as the San Rafael Hospital, which has announced that the planned surgical treatment is only open to new, strictly urgent, emerging diseases that can not be postponed.

On March 8, a special committee led by Lombardy ËßÅ LombardiaÔºåReg. President Attilio Fondana and Health Commissioner Giulio Gallera decided to make intensive-care unit and acute hospital beds available as soon as possible, beds are being added in operating rooms, corridors and recovery rooms, but they are not being added at the same rate as patients and they are not being completely isolated. Hospitals in Cremona, Lodi and Bergamo are at full capacity.

Other regions such as Piedmont 36, Amelia Romagn√© 37, Tuscany 38, Lazio 39, Liguria 40, Marche 41 and other regions of the Comprehensive Appointment Center (Cup) suspended general medical activities of outpatient, examination and treatment appointments, only medical activities with codes U (emergency) and B (short-term) : Treatment / rehabilitation that can not be delayed such as chemotherapy and radiotherapy, blood transfusions, ongoing experimental treatment regimens, alternative therapies, and diagnostic procedures designed to activate and / or follow-up such as vaccination, cancer screening, post-surgical examination, scheduled diagnostic treatment and procedures, general anesthesia, such as lumbar puncture, medullary puncture, MRI and CT diagnosis of emergency or non-deferrable activities; plaster fixation or Removal Activities; dialysis treatment.

In addition, some special hospitals have also adjusted their diagnosis and treatment activities, for example, prenatal diagnosis is retained during pregnancy and maternity protection at the Children's Hospital of Genoa Sriini 42, time-dependent neonatal screening (neonatal ultrasound, acoustic screening and red light reflex testing and cystic fibrosis screening) , but canceling prenatal classes.

5. Recovery and discharge

On February 28, the Department of Health Released Document 43, which defines the terms "clinical remission" and "Guarito" for new coronary pneumonia. According to the Ministry of Health, an infected person can be considered clinically cured if he or she presents with clinical symptoms and then the symptoms disappear (that is, become asymptomatic) . Clinically recovered patients may still test positive for the virus. A full recovery (Guarito) is a clinical recovery, at least 24 hours apart after the two tests were negative. There is also a need to distinguish between cases of complete clearance of SARS-CoV-2(clearance / eliminazione) and more stringent criteria.

The European Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (ECDC) says 44 patients should be discharged based on clinical, viral and serological criteria when medical resources are available, but the criteria may be adjusted in times of stress. The ECDC also points out that patients with mild illness can be discharged early, subject to a 14-day quarantine under conditions that meet the required standards, such as providing a well-ventilated single room, wearing a mask, reducing contact with family members, eating alone, keeping hands clean, and prohibiting travel, and Track the patient's health.

La Stampa had previously reported a case of recovery in an 81-year-old woman. After a week of hospitalization, Amanda Bottini recovered clinically and was discharged from San Matteo Hospital in Pavia after testing negative for the virus three times. Ms. Bottini was able to dine with her family and play with her children and grandchildren the day after she returned home, the report said.

By 18 p.m. on March 15, Italy had 2,335 patients who had met the criteria for recovery, and the death toll had risen to 1,809. The statistics of cure rate and death rate in each region are as follows:

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Figure 7

The outbreak has had a huge impact on the northern part of Italy, where medical resources are the most abundant, bringing to the surface hidden problems in the structure and number of medical staff, the number of beds per 1,000 people and so on, the imbalance in the distribution of health-care resources based on regions is also alarming the rest of Italy. To remedy the situation, local health institutions, in conjunction with departments such as the Ministry of Civil Defense and the Ministry of national defense, have accelerated the activation of standby medical resources, trying to take into account other urgent medical needs while consolidating the fight against the epidemic, and to share the pressure for key epidemic areas. In addition, the Italian health system focuses on the design of diagnostic testing procedures and isolation / discharge observation procedures in order to avoid the risk of cross-infection and to prevent further expansion of the epidemic.

At present, the development of the epidemic in Italy is not yet clear. The battle against the virus knows no borders. Let us hope that the global fight against the epidemic will be brought to an early dawn and people's lives will return to peace.
